    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-08-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-08-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="306"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d306">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Adams</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Seward</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1028.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States,</hi>
                            <hi rend="italic">London,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-08-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 10, 1865</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>SIR: * * * * * * * * *</p>
                <p>In obedience to the instructions contained in No. 1481, of the 20th of July, I
                    have addressed a note to Lord Russell, demanding the restoration of the schooner
                    St. Mary’s, remaining at Anotta bay, in the island of Jamaica. Owing to the
                    absence of the necessary dates, it was difficult to prepare a statement of facts
                    in any other than a tentative manner, and still more so to rest an argument upon
                    them. The case, however, appears to be tolerably clear.</p>
                <p>I have the honor to be, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>CHARLES FRANCIS ADAMS.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">William H. Seward,</hi>
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State, Washington, D. C.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
